Overview of Analysis

In this analysis, I create a regression model that uses physiochemical properties of wine to predict the wine quality score. This model will allow Winemakers at Wine Inc. to better understand what levels of physiochemical properties lead to a better wine quality score for their variants of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. This regression model will help Wine Inc. to produce higher quality wine, which in turn may help to increase sales revenue and brand reputation. This analysis may also help to decrease costs associated with creating new types of wine through trial and error because Winemakers within the company will have a statistically supported understanding of how each physiochemical property of the wine impacts the quality score.

For this analysis, we use R version 3.6.1. Further detail regarding the session information and packages used can be seen in the appendix section. Be sure to have the correct version of R and packages installed or there may be issues with reproducibility.

# Install pacman if it is not already installed
if (!require("pacman")) install.packages("pacman")
# Load in necessary packages
pacman::p_load(DataExplorer, corrplot, curl, caret)

Data Description

I have accessed wine quality data from the University of California, Irvines Machine Learning Repository. There are two datasets related to red and white variants of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. One dataset is for the white variants, and one is for the red variants. We access these datasets directly via the curl package, but the link to manually download these two datasets is below in case there are any issues: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/wine+quality

Before performing exploratory analysis, we first must combine the 2 datasets into 1. This is done by adding a Color variable on each dataset and then rbinding the datasets together.

# Read in 2 datasets. 1 dataset is for white wine and the other dataset is for red wine. 
white <- read.csv(curl("https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/wine-quality/winequality-white.csv"), sep = ";")

red <- read.csv(curl("https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/wine-quality/winequality-red.csv"), sep = ";")

# Create a column to specify the color of the wine for both datasets. 
white$Color <- "White"
red$Color <- "Red"

# Combine the red and white datasets together
wine <- white
wine <- rbind(wine, red)

# Change the data type for the Color variable to be a factor
wine$Color <- as.factor(wine$Color)

Now, we can properly describe the dataset. In our dataset, there are 6497 total observations and 13 variables. We have 12 numeric variables and 1 factor (Color) that has 2 categories: red and white.

# Subset the data down to just the numeric variables

Preprocessing

The key preprocessing that needs to be done for this analysis is eliminating outliers from the numeric variables. We do not need to perform any imputations due to there being no missing values.

# Remove the 2 outliers with very high chloride levels
wine <- wine[ which(wine$chlorides <= .4),]

# Remove the 2 outliers with very high citric acid levels
wine <- wine[ which(wine$citric.acid <= 1),]

# Remove the 1 outlier with a high density level
wine <- wine[ which(wine$density < 1.02),]

# Remove the 1 outlier with a very high free sulfur dioxide level that was over 100 points higher than the second highest value
wine <- wine[ which(wine$free.sulfur.dioxide <= 150),]

# Remove the 3 outliers with high sulphate levels
wine <- wine[ which(wine$sulphates <= 1.7),]

# Remove the 1 outlier with a high volatile acidity level
wine <- wine[ which(wine$volatile.acidity < 1.4),]

These are the resulting distributions of values for each variable after removing outliers. The distributions appear more normal and less skewed.

# Plot histograms for the numeric variables
plot_histogram(wine)

Modeling

Before modeling, we randomly split our data into training and testing datasets. We use 70% of the observations to train the model and 30% of the observations to test the model performance on data that the model was not trained on. We do this so that we can more effectively evaluate model performance.

# Set sample size to be 70% of the total data
sampleSize <- .70 * nrow(wine)

## set the seed to make the partition reproducible
set.seed(100)

# Generate the random indexes that will be used for the training dataset
train_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(wine)), size = sampleSize)

# Create training and testing datasets
train <- wine[train_ind, ]
test <- wine[-train_ind, ]

Now that we have the data split into training and testing datasets, we can build a stepwise mutiple linear regression model. The results of this model can be seen below.

# Create null and full models on the training data
null = lm(quality ~ 1, data = train)
full = lm(quality ~ ., data = train)

# Build a stepwise mutiple linear regression model
stepwise = step(null, scope = list(lower = null, upper = full), direction = "both", trace = 0, k = 2)

# Show the accuracy of the model on the training data
summary(stepwise)

We have built our model using the training data, so we can now evaluate it using our testing data.

The Root Mean Squared Error of our model on the test data is .734.

# Predict the wine quality scores for the test data
testPred <- predict(stepwise, newdata = test)

RMSE(testPred, test$quality)
## [1] 0.7307591

The R Squared vaule for our model on the test data is .302.

R2(testPred, test$quality)
## [1] 0.302178

These two values are comparable to, and actually slightly better than, the performance on the training data. This means that the model was not overfit to the training data and can be used in practice on external data.
